The option forces the library to build without thread support.

Main changes:

1. Remove `libpthread` from the list of link-time dependencies.

2. Implements stubs for `cv::Mutex` and `cv::AutoLock`.

3. Disable the parts of `cv::AsyncArray` that depend on multi-threaded
   code.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/fpetrogalli/opencv/commits/674215c574b498aa1521af3162319014f7fd4e37"},{"sha":"cf8c7480392440b7d622cebeb0b2ae8ebb27393d","author":{"name":"Francesco Petrogalli","email":"743152b921210732b2796f9fe9db99ef50b10ebc@arm.com"},"message":"[build][option] Build option to disable filesystem support.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/fpetrogalli/opencv/commits/cf8c7480392440b7d622cebeb0b2ae8ebb27393d"},{"sha":"3f50e14dbe461fc64c45ce222435bbc7bd9a01f9","author":{"name":"Francesco Petrogalli","email":"743152b921210732b2796f9fe9db99ef50b10ebc@arm.com"},"message":"[baremetal][aarch64] Build a baremetal OpenCV for AArch64.

This patch provide a toolchain file that allows to build the library
for baremetal applications. Minimal changes have been applied to the
code to be able to compile with a baremetal toolchain.

The option `CV_BAREMETAL` is used to guard the bits in the code that
are baremetal-specific.

The toolchain file requires the path to the baremetal
toolchain. Example cmake invocation:

    cmake ../opencv/ \
    -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=../opencv/platforms/baremetal/aarch64.toolchain.cmake \
    -DBAREMETAL_TOOLCHAIN_PATH=/absolute/path/to/gcc-baremetal-toolchain/bin/ \
    -DBUILD_EXAMPLES=ON

A barematel toolchain for targeting aarch64 can be found at [1], under
`aarch64-none-elf`.

[1] https://developer.arm.com/tools-and-software/open-source-software/developer-tools/gnu-toolchain/gnu-a/downloads

The current patch covers the following modules

--   OpenCV modules:
--     To be built:                 core features2d highgui imgcodecs imgproc ml photo video
--     Disabled:                    flann ts videoio world
--     Disabled by dependency:      calib3d objdetect stitching
--     Unavailable:                 dnn gapi java python2 python3
--     Applications:                examples apps

The folder `samples/baremetal` provides two example baremetal applications.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/fpetrogalli/opencv/commits/3f50e14dbe461fc64c45ce222435bbc7bd9a01f9"}]

[html generation]
html = analyzer.ModelAnalyzer.Analyze(tflite_input, 'html')

[local webserver]
analyzer.ModelAnalyzer.Analyze(tflite_input, 'webserver')

Also updates build_pip_package_with_bazel.sh to include it with tflite_runtime.

Change-Id: I5cc3a70776c51e629f35d92ac3eba1e1f88c0d5d","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/c6f71c50db479cdaaa55cbfdd66ba41a77c86b9a"},{"sha":"05963dfc0aea5f8b26f0f85a84787b3f4f771db0","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix catastrophic cancellation in Jacobi eigendecomposition convergence test.

Computing the off_diag_norm as (frobenius_norm - diag_norm) suffers from cancellation problems when we get close to convergence. Instead, compute the off-diagonal norm directly.

Raise the default tolerance to 1e-5 to avoid regressing performance. This is a reasonable thing to do since we are now actually enforcing the tolerance a bit better; previously everything cancelled to zero when we got close to such a small tolerance value.

Also update the XLA:Python bindings to use the same tol/max_iters defaults as the C++ API.

[{"sha":"5c0b694ef3a4b86cdcd7ce03f1b300252ca70a05","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"container: make hostconfig.json non-world-readable (0600)

When writing container's `hostconfig.json`, permissions were set to 0644 (world-
readable). While this is not a security concern (as the `/var/lib/docker/containers`
directory has `0700` or `0701` permissions), there is no real need to have these
permissions, as this file is only accessed by the daemon.

Looking at history for file permissions;

- 06b53e3fc7aca2b3dae32edab08c7662d3e9e7e8 (first implementation) used `0666` (world-writable)
- cf1a6c08fa03aa7020f8f5b414bb9349a9c8371a refactored the code, and removed explicit permissions
- ea3cbd3274664f5b16fce78d7df036f6b5c94e30 introduced atomic writes, and brought back the `0666` permissions
- 3ec8fed7476704f061891d4c421c615da49e30c7 removed world-writable bits, but kept world-readable

This patch updates the permissions to `0600`, matching what's used for `config.v2.json`,
which was updated in ae52cea3ab46e1e728606349fb6baa9a8203f3ed, but forgot to update
`hostconfig.json`.

> (..) the first four of these are the standard built-in build-arg options

> add the following line to the dockerfile:
>
> ARG all_proxy

Given the we support all other commonly known proxy env-vars by default, it makes
sense to add this one as well.

Change-Id: Icecbb71f1c385b2cc7fbc9dee01862fb4882eb24","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lisphacker/tensorflow/commits/9df99991066cb80caedf4579c04ee0a213b7bde6"},{"sha":"80d8d2525f148541c83a0a989a0663a24d747262","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Include both the global and thread-local extra jit context in the JIT signature.

Previously if there was a thread-local context set we would include it in preference to the global context. However since the "extra context" is an opaque object with no particular semantics as far as the C++ code is concerned, it makes more sense to include both local and global as part of the cache key. Just because the thread-local values are equal it doesn't mean that they completely override the global values.

effects, then the fiber won't have a PassiveStatic effect flag, which
will trigger the "missing expected subtreeFlag" warning.

Change-Id: I5cc3a70776c51e629f35d92ac3eba1e1f88c0d5d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/tensorflow/commits/c6f71c50db479cdaaa55cbfdd66ba41a77c86b9a"},{"sha":"05963dfc0aea5f8b26f0f85a84787b3f4f771db0","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix catastrophic cancellation in Jacobi eigendecomposition convergence test.

Computing the off_diag_norm as (frobenius_norm - diag_norm) suffers from cancellation problems when we get close to convergence. Instead, compute the off-diagonal norm directly.

Raise the default tolerance to 1e-5 to avoid regressing performance. This is a reasonable thing to do since we are now actually enforcing the tolerance a bit better; previously everything cancelled to zero when we got close to such a small tolerance value.

Also update the XLA:Python bindings to use the same tol/max_iters defaults as the C++ API.

Change-Id: Ice2e722179b46090d28a26fb1d3346bfcc131ebf","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/tensorflow/commits/42fb47a60cd5d88321781e366d768e88c61ac7b4"},{"sha":"1bebe43aef5d89618b717a8c36f660a10e12582c","author":{"name":"Feng Liu","email":"3f098ac60ccdd3d0addfa2e58b2df0bb47e6eba5@google.com"},"message":"Add quantization related TFR built-in ops

Four TFR built-in ops are added to write quantization related composition.

"tfr.quant_raw_data" and "tfr.quant_qparam" are added to handle the quantized
type of the input tensors.

"tfr.quant_rescale" is added since the specific implementation depends on the
platform, i.e. floating-point rescale or integer shiftt/multiple. With this
abstraction, we can legalize it to the platform specific operations later on.

"tfr.quant_act_range" is added to simplify the composition implementation. This
can also be modeled as a new composite op.

[html generation]
html = analyzer.ModelAnalyzer.Analyze(tflite_input, 'html')

  output_file.write(html)

[local webserver]

Previously, DevTools recursed over both children and siblings during mount. This caused potential stack overflows when there were a lot of children (e.g. a list containing many items).

Given the following example component tree:

       A
    B  C  D
    E     F
          G

A method that recurses for every child and sibling leads to a max depth of 6:

    A
    A -> B
    A -> B -> E
    A -> B -> C
    A -> B -> C -> D
    A -> B -> C -> D -> F
    A -> B -> C -> D -> F -> G

The stack gets deeper as the tree gets either deeper or wider.

A method that recurses for every child and iterates over siblings leads to a max depth of 4:

    A
    A -> B
    A -> B -> E
    A -> C
    A -> D
    A -> D -> F
    A -> D -> F -> G

The stack gets deeper as the tree gets deeper but is resilient to wide trees (e.g. lists containing many items).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/a0d6b155dc3a182162b9f91baac33df39d7919df"},{"sha":"7edd6281344a35519ca36b8a8280e7ba37187004","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Removed (deleted) tracing fixture test from relesae scripts","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/7edd6281344a35519ca36b8a8280e7ba37187004"},{"sha":"2a7bb4154809f1f4e17ffbdde1342bd4ce91ea37","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Preparing DevTools 4.12.4 -> 4.13.0 release (#21378)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/2a7bb4154809f1f4e17ffbdde1342bd4ce91ea37"},{"sha":"207d4c3a535d4624f17634baa6bfe613f5f3e4e6","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Revert "Support nesting of startTransition and flushSync (alt) (#21149)"

This reverts commit 2e7aceeb5c8b6e5c61174c0e9731e263e956e445.

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

been reported as an issue, and we'd have to do additional work to
distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all

When called from inside an effect, flushSync cannot synchronously flush
its updates because React is already working. So we fire a warning.

However, we should still change the priority of the updates to sync so

back to a fiber tree.

completely eliminate those, it may still be worth the extra work to

Change-Id: Icecbb71f1c385b2cc7fbc9dee01862fb4882eb24","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ashutosh1919/tensorflow/commits/9df99991066cb80caedf4579c04ee0a213b7bde6"},{"sha":"80d8d2525f148541c83a0a989a0663a24d747262","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Include both the global and thread-local extra jit context in the JIT signature.

Previously if there was a thread-local context set we would include it in preference to the global context. However since the "extra context" is an opaque object with no particular semantics as far as the C++ code is concerned, it makes more sense to include both local and global as part of the cache key. Just because the thread-local values are equal it doesn't mean that they completely override the global values.

Change-Id: Icecbb71f1c385b2cc7fbc9dee01862fb4882eb24","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ashutosh1919/tensorflow/commits/9df99991066cb80caedf4579c04ee0a213b7bde6"},{"sha":"80d8d2525f148541c83a0a989a0663a24d747262","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Include both the global and thread-local extra jit context in the JIT signature.

Previously if there was a thread-local context set we would include it in preference to the global context. However since the "extra context" is an opaque object with no particular semantics as far as the C++ code is concerned, it makes more sense to include both local and global as part of the cache key. Just because the thread-local values are equal it doesn't mean that they completely override the global values.
